Real-time scenario-based AWS EC2 Interview Questions & Answers:
This will cover all aspects: EC2 basics, instances, storage, networking, security, auto-scaling, monitoring, cost optimization, high availability, DevOps, troubleshooting, and real-world scenarios.
1 Q: What is Amazon EC2? 
A: EC2 is a web service that provides resizable compute capacity in the cloud, allowing users to launch virtual servers with different instance types, operating systems, and configurations.
2 Q: Scenario: You need a virtual server to host a web application for 1 year. Which EC2 pricing model is cost-efficient? 
A: Reserved Instances for 1-year term to save costs compared to on-demand.
3 Q: Difference between EC2 and Lambda? 
A: EC2 = full server control, long-running workloads. Lambda = serverless, short-duration functions with no server management.
4.Q: Scenario: You want ephemeral compute for batch jobs. Which instance type? 
A: Spot Instances for cost savings.
5.Q: What are EC2 instance types? 
A: General Purpose (t3/t4), Compute Optimized (c5), Memory Optimized (r5), Storage Optimized (i3), GPU Instances (p4/g4), etc.
6.Q: Scenario: Your app needs 4 vCPUs and 16GB RAM. Which instance type class? A: General Purpose (e.g., t3.xlarge) or Compute Optimized if CPU-bound.
7.Q: Difference between on-demand, reserved, spot, and savings plan? A: On-demand = pay per hour, no commitment. Reserved = 1–3 year commitment, cheaper. Spot = spare capacity at discount, can be interrupted. Savings plan = flexible discounted pricing for compute usage.
8.Q: Scenario: You need instances for dev/test environment that can stop/start frequently. Which pricing model? A: On-demand for flexibility or spot if interruptions are acceptable.
9.Q: What is an Amazon Machine Image (AMI)? A: A pre-configured template containing OS, application server, and apps to launch EC2 instances.
10.Q: Scenario: You need the same instance configuration in multiple regions. How? A: Copy the AMI to target regions and launch instances.
11.Q: How do you access EC2 instances? A: SSH for Linux, RDP for Windows.
12.Q: Scenario: You lost your private key for SSH. How to access Linux EC2? A: Stop instance, detach root volume, attach to another instance, update ~/.ssh/authorized_keys, reattach, start instance.
13.Q: What are instance states? A: Pending, Running, Stopping, Stopped, Shutting-down, Terminated.
14.Q: Scenario: Your EC2 instance is stopped but billing continues. Why? A: EBS volume attached and provisioned Elastic IP incurs charges.
15.Q: What are Elastic IPs? A: Static public IPv4 addresses for EC2, which can be remapped to other instances.
16.Q: Scenario: Elastic IP attached but not in use. Any cost implications? A: Yes, AWS charges for unattached Elastic IPs.
17.Q: Difference between instance store and EBS? A: Instance store = ephemeral storage tied to instance lifecycle. EBS = persistent block storage.
18.Q: Scenario: Instance store lost data after reboot. Why? A: Instance store is ephemeral; data is lost when instance stops or terminates.
19.Q: What is EC2 User Data? A: Script executed during instance launch to configure the instance automatically.
20.Q: Scenario: You need auto-installation of Apache/Nginx on instance launch. How? A: Add shell commands in User Data script.
21.Q: What is EC2 metadata service? A: Provides instance info (instance-id, security groups, AMI ID) accessible via HTTP endpoint.
22.Q: Scenario: You want dynamic configuration from instance itself. How? A: Use EC2 Instance Metadata Service (IMDS v2 recommended).
23.Q: What is an instance profile? A: Attaches IAM role to EC2 instance for AWS API access.
24.Q: Scenario: EC2 needs to read/write S3 bucket securely. How? A: Attach IAM role via instance profile with S3 permissions.
25.Q: Can an EC2 instance have multiple ENIs? A: Yes, supported depending on instance type.
26.Q: Scenario: You need private and public network interfaces on same instance. How? A: Attach multiple ENIs and configure routing/security groups.
27.Q: What is a placement group? A: A logical grouping to influence instance placement (clustered, spread, partition) for performance/HA.
28.Q: Scenario: Low-latency HPC workload. Which placement strategy? A: Cluster placement group.
29.Q: Difference between Cluster, Spread, and Partition placement groups? A: Cluster = high throughput/low latency. Spread = isolate instances across hosts for failure domain. Partition = divides instances into logical partitions for HA.
30.Q: Scenario: Need fault-tolerant architecture across AZs. Which placement group? A: Spread or Partition placement group.
31.Q: Can you change EC2 instance type after launch? A: Yes, stop instance → modify instance type → start.
32.Q: Scenario: You need more CPU for few hours. How to scale? A: Resize instance (vertical scaling) or use Auto Scaling group with launch template.
33.Q: What is EC2 Auto Scaling? A: Automatically adjusts number of instances based on demand using scaling policies.
34.Q: Scenario: Traffic spikes 10x daily at 6 PM. How to manage cost/performance? A: Use Auto Scaling scheduled policies to scale out/in at 6 PM and off-peak.
35.Q: Difference between horizontal and vertical scaling? A: Horizontal = add/remove instances. Vertical = change instance type.
36.Q: What is EC2 launch template? A: Template containing instance configuration (AMI, instance type, key pair, security groups) for launching instances.
37.Q: Scenario: Multiple ASGs require same configuration. Solution? A: Use Launch Template across ASGs.
38.Q: Can you attach EBS volume to running EC2? A: Yes, online attach/detach supported.
39.Q: Scenario: Need increased storage for Linux EC2 without downtime. How? A: Use EBS elastic volume modification, extend filesystem online.
40.Q: Can you encrypt EBS volumes? A: Yes, using KMS-managed keys.
41.Q: Scenario: Need encryption for existing unencrypted volume. How? A: Take snapshot → copy with encryption enabled → create new volume → attach.
42.Q: Difference between instance store-backed vs EBS-backed instance? A: Instance store-backed loses data on stop. EBS-backed persists.
43.Q: What is EC2 hibernation? A: Saves instance RAM to EBS and stops instance; resumes quickly with OS state intact.
44.Q: Scenario: Long-running process needs paused state. Solution? A: Enable EC2 hibernation.
45.Q: Can you attach multiple EBS volumes to same instance? A: Yes, limited by instance type ENI and volume count limits.
46.Q: How to monitor EC2 health? A: Use CloudWatch metrics, Status Checks, and CloudTrail.
47.Q: Scenario: Instance failed System Status Check. Next steps? A: Stop/start instance, check underlying hardware, contact AWS if persistent.
48.Q: Scenario: Instance failed Instance Status Check. Fix? A: Check OS boot logs, disk issues, SSH connectivity, kernel panic.
49.Q: What is EC2 placement tenancy? A: Default (shared hardware) vs Dedicated host (physical server fully for you).
50.Q: Scenario: Compliance requires dedicated physical host. Solution? A: Use Dedicated Host tenancy.
51–100: Networking & Security
51.Q: How does EC2 connect to VPC? A: EC2 is launched in a subnet within VPC; connectivity controlled via route tables, internet gateway, NAT, and security groups.
52.Q: Scenario: EC2 needs private subnet access to internet. How? A: Use NAT gateway/instance in public subnet.
53.Q: Difference between Security Groups and NACLs? A: Security Group = instance-level firewall (stateful). NACL = subnet-level firewall (stateless).
54.Q: Scenario: All traffic blocked despite security group open. Why? A: Check NACL rules; may be denying traffic.
55.Q: What is Elastic Load Balancer (ELB) with EC2? A: Distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances.
56.Q: Scenario: Need high availability for web app. Solution? A: Use EC2 instances across AZs behind ALB.
57.Q: Difference between ALB, NLB, CLB? A: ALB = HTTP/HTTPS, path-based routing. NLB = TCP, high performance. CLB = legacy.
58.Q: Scenario: Need SSL termination at load balancer. Which ELB? A: Application Load Balancer.
59.Q: What is VPC endpoint for EC2? A: Private connection to AWS services without internet access.
60.Q: Scenario: EC2 must access S3 without public IP. Solution? A: Use S3 VPC Endpoint (Gateway type).
61.Q: How to implement security patching on EC2? A: Use Systems Manager Patch Manager or manual updates via SSH/SSM.
62.Q: Scenario: Need to patch hundreds of EC2 Linux instances automatically. Solution? A: Use AWS Systems Manager Patch Manager with patch baselines.
63.Q: How to enable MFA for EC2 access? A: IAM policies + MFA enforced on AWS console/API; EC2 SSH uses key pair.
64.Q: What is EC2 key pair? A: Public-private key pair for SSH/RDP authentication.
65.Q: Scenario: Lost private key for production instance. Fix? A: Stop instance → detach volume → attach to another instance → add new key to authorized_keys.
66.Q: How to restrict EC2 API access? A: Use IAM roles, policies, and VPC endpoint policies.
67.Q: Scenario: EC2 instance compromised. Immediate action? A: Isolate in security group, snapshot volume, analyze, rotate keys/credentials.
68.Q: Difference between default VPC and custom VPC? A: Default VPC = preconfigured with public subnets. Custom = fully configurable.
69.Q: Scenario: Multi-tier architecture with public web, private app, DB subnet. How? 
A: Public subnet → ALB + web EC2. Private subnet → app EC2 + DB RDS. NAT for outbound internet from private subnet.
70.Q: How to enforce HTTPS only on EC2? A: Configure Security Groups to allow only 443; optionally enforce via ALB listener rules.
71.Q: How to limit SSH access to specific IPs? A: Security Group inbound rule with specific CIDR.
72.Q: Scenario: SSH from dynamic ISP IPs. Solution? A: Use bastion host with dynamic IP allowed, or VPN connection to VPC.
73.Q: What is EC2 instance metadata service v2? A: Session-oriented API for instance metadata with IMDSv2 for security.
74.Q: Scenario: Prevent SSRF attacks exploiting metadata service. Solution? A: Enforce IMDSv2 requirement.
75.Q: How to enable private DNS hostname for EC2? A: Enable enableDnsHostnames and enableDnsSupport in VPC.
76.Q: Scenario: EC2 cannot resolve DNS. Fix? A: Check VPC DNS settings, DHCP options, security group egress rules.
77.Q: Difference between public and private IP on EC2? A: Public IP = internet routable. Private IP = internal VPC routing only.
78.Q: Scenario: EC2 in private subnet needs RDP to Windows. How? A: Use bastion host or Systems Manager Session Manager.
79.Q: What is source/destination check? A: Enabled by default; prevents instance from routing traffic not destined for itself.
80.Q: Scenario: NAT instance cannot route traffic. Fix? A: Disable source/destination check.
81.Q: How to attach multiple IP addresses to EC2? A: Use multiple private IPs via secondary ENI.
82.Q: Scenario: Multi-homed EC2 for hybrid cloud. Approach? A: Attach multiple ENIs for public/private connections.
83.Q: How to implement EC2 security compliance auditing? A: Use Config rules, CloudTrail, and Security Hub.
84.Q: Scenario: Detect unauthorized AMI launches. How? A: CloudTrail + Config rules on AMI creation.
85.Q: Difference between Security Group stateful vs NACL stateless? A: Security Group allows response traffic automatically. NACL must explicitly allow return traffic.
86.Q: Scenario: Web server in public subnet but cannot serve clients. Check? A: SG inbound, route table, subnet ACL, internet gateway attachment.
87.Q: Scenario: Windows EC2 cannot RDP. Likely reasons? A: Security group inbound 3389, Network ACL, firewall, or RDP service disabled.
88.Q: How to configure bastion host securely? A: Public subnet, hardened AMI, limited SSH access, CloudWatch logging.
89.Q: Scenario: Bastion host compromised. Steps? A: Isolate, snapshot volume, rotate keys, review CloudTrail, redeploy hardened host.
90.Q: How to restrict EC2 internet access? A: Remove IGW/NAT, security group rules, NACLs, or use private subnet.
91.Q: What is Security Group reference? A: Allows SG to reference another SG as source/destination.
92.Q: Scenario: App server allowed only DB server to connect. How? A: Security group referencing DB server SG.
93.Q: Can EC2 instances in different regions communicate privately? A: No direct private IP. Use VPN/Transit Gateway.
94.Q: What is EC2 placement group impact on networking? A: Cluster PG → low-latency, high-throughput. Spread PG → isolated.
95.Q: Scenario: EC2 network throughput low. Check? A: Instance type network limits, ENI attachment, placement group.
96.Q: What is ENI? A: Elastic Network Interface, virtual NIC attached to EC2.
97.Q: Scenario: High availability web servers. Solution? A: Multi-AZ deployment, ALB, Auto Scaling.
98.Q: Scenario: Need private EC2 to access S3 with no IGW. How? A: Use S3 VPC Endpoint.
99.Q: Scenario: NAT gateway fails. What happens? A: Private subnet loses internet connectivity.
100.Q: Difference between NAT instance and NAT gateway? A: NAT gateway = managed, scalable, redundant. NAT instance = self-managed, less scalable.
101–150: Storage – EBS, Instance Store, EFS, S3 Integration
101.Q: Difference between instance store and EBS? A: Instance store = ephemeral, tied to instance lifecycle; EBS = persistent block storage.
102.Q: Scenario: EC2 rebooted, instance store data lost. Why? A: Instance store is ephemeral; data does not persist across stop/start.
103.Q: Can you attach EBS to running EC2? A: Yes, online attach/detach supported.
104.Q: Scenario: Need to increase EBS volume size without downtime. How? A: Use Elastic Volume Modification → extend filesystem.
105.Q: Can EBS volumes be encrypted? A: Yes, using AWS KMS-managed keys.
106.Q: Scenario: Existing unencrypted EBS. How to encrypt? A: Take snapshot → copy with encryption enabled → create new volume → attach.
107.Q: What is EBS volume types? A: gp3/gp2 (General Purpose SSD), io2/io1 (Provisioned IOPS SSD), st1 (Throughput Optimized HDD), sc1 (Cold HDD).
108.Q: Scenario: High IOPS database workload. Which volume type? A: io2/io1 with provisioned IOPS.
109.Q: How does EBS snapshot work? A: Incremental backup stored in S3.
110.Q: Scenario: Need cross-region backup. Solution? A: Copy EBS snapshot to target region.
111.Q: What is EFS? A: Elastic File System – fully managed, scalable NFS file system for multiple EC2 access.
112.Q: Scenario: Multiple EC2 instances need shared filesystem. Which service? A: EFS with NFS mount.
113.Q: Difference between EBS and EFS? A: EBS = block storage, one instance; EFS = file storage, multiple instances concurrently.
114.Q: Scenario: EC2 instance needs temporary storage. Which option? A: Instance store for ephemeral fast storage.
115.Q: Can EBS volumes be attached to multiple instances? A: No, except EBS Multi-Attach supported for io1/io2 volumes in Linux.
116.Q: Scenario: EC2 in multi-AZ with shared volume. Solution? A: Use EFS or FSx for shared access, EBS Multi-Attach in same AZ.
117.
Q: How to monitor EBS performance? A: CloudWatch metrics: VolumeReadOps, VolumeWriteOps, VolumeReadBytes, VolumeWriteBytes, BurstBalance.
118.
Q: Scenario: VolumeWriteOps high, instance slow. Solution? A: Increase volume type/IOPS, check instance network limits.
119.
Q: How to resize EFS storage? A: Automatic scaling; no manual resizing needed.
120.
Q: Scenario: EC2 cannot mount EFS. Check? A: Security group allows NFS (2049), correct VPC/subnet, mount target exists.
121–150: Storage – EBS/EFS, S3, Snapshots
121.
Q: Scenario: EC2 root volume running out of space. How to extend? A: Use Elastic Volume Modification → extend EBS volume → resize filesystem (xfs_growfs or resize2fs).
122.
Q: Scenario: EBS snapshot restores slowly. Solution? A: Enable Fast Snapshot Restore for region-specific instant availability.
123.
Q: EC2 needs high-throughput storage for big data. Options? A: Use st1 (Throughput Optimized HDD) or EFS depending on shared access needs.
124.
Q: Scenario: Multi-instance application requires shared file system. How? A: Mount EFS with NFS across instances.
125.
Q: Can EBS volumes be resized while attached? A: Yes, online resizing supported; extend filesystem afterward.
126.
Q: Scenario: Instance requires both high IOPS and encryption. Which volume type? A: io2/io2 Block Express with KMS encryption.
127.
Q: EC2 needs cross-region backup for compliance. How? A: Copy EBS snapshots or AMIs to target region.
128.
Q: Scenario: EBS volume attached to wrong instance. Solution? A: Detach, attach to correct instance; ensure OS recognizes device.
129.
Q: What is EBS Multi-Attach? A: io1/io2 volumes can be attached to multiple Linux instances in the same AZ for shared access.
130.
Q: Scenario: Application requires read-only shared storage across AZs. How? A: Use S3 or EFS (multi-AZ support).
131.
Q: How to monitor EBS performance? A: CloudWatch metrics: VolumeReadOps, VolumeWriteOps, VolumeThroughputPercentage, BurstBalance.
132.
Q: Scenario: VolumeWriteOps high, performance lag. Solution? A: Increase IOPS, upgrade instance type, check network limits.
133.
Q: EC2 requires backup of ephemeral data. How? A: Copy data to EBS snapshot or S3, as instance store is ephemeral.
134.
Q: Scenario: Need encrypted EBS after instance launch. How? A: Snapshot existing volume → copy snapshot with encryption → create encrypted volume → attach.
135.
Q: What is difference between gp2 and gp3 EBS volumes? A: gp3 = provisioned IOPS & throughput independently; cheaper & better performance flexibility.
136.
Q: Scenario: Multiple EC2s need access to shared file system. Solution? A: Use EFS with NFS mounts; scalable & concurrent access.
137.
Q: EC2 needs high IOPS for database. Which volume type? A: io2 Block Express for sub-millisecond latency.
138.
Q: Scenario: EBS snapshot costs rising. Solution? A: Delete old snapshots, automate with Lifecycle Manager policies.
139.
Q: EC2 ephemeral storage lost on stop. Solution for persistence? A: Migrate to EBS or EFS depending on shared access requirements.
140.
Q: Scenario: Need to restore instance quickly in DR. Solution? A: Use AMI + snapshot → launch new EC2 quickly.
141.
Q: EC2 needs cross-AZ shared storage. Option? A: EFS with mount targets in each AZ.
142.
Q: Scenario: Large dataset read-heavy, multiple instances. Which storage? A: EFS (for shared read), S3 (for object-based), or combination.
143.
Q: How to secure EBS volumes? A: Enable encryption (KMS), IAM roles for access, snapshots encrypted.
144.
Q: Scenario: Volume attached but not recognized by OS. Fix? A: Rescan devices, check /dev/ path, mount filesystem.
145.
Q: How to migrate instance store data to persistent storage? A: Copy files to EBS volume or S3 before instance termination.
146.
Q: Scenario: EC2 needs high throughput temporary storage. Option? A: Instance store for ephemeral fast storage.
147.
Q: EC2 EBS volume detached accidentally. How to recover? A: Reattach; ensure filesystem integrity and mount properly.
148.
Q: Scenario: EC2 root volume corrupted. How to recover? A: Detach volume, attach to rescue instance, repair filesystem, reattach.
149.
Q: EBS snapshot can restore to larger volume? A: Yes, volume size can be increased during restore.
150.
Q: Scenario: EC2 requires daily automated backup. How? A: Use EBS snapshot with Lifecycle Manager or CloudWatch scheduled Lambda scripts.
151–200: Auto Scaling & High Availability
151.
Q: What is EC2 Auto Scaling? A: Automatically adjusts number of EC2 instances based on load.
152.
Q: Scenario: Traffic spikes at 6 PM daily. How to scale? A: Use scheduled scaling policies in Auto Scaling Group (ASG).
153.
Q: Difference between horizontal and vertical scaling? A: Horizontal = add/remove instances; Vertical = change instance type.
154.
Q: Scenario: Need to scale memory-heavy workload. Approach? A: Vertical scaling: change to higher memory instance.
155.
Q: How does ASG detect unhealthy instance? A: Health checks (EC2 status checks, ELB health checks).
156.
Q: Scenario: ASG not replacing failed instance. Check? A: Ensure health check type and grace period configured correctly.
157.
Q: What is launch configuration vs launch template? A: Launch configuration = static template; Launch template = versioned, flexible, supports multiple ASGs.
158.
Q: Scenario: Multiple ASGs with same config. Solution? A: Use Launch Template.
159.
Q: How to implement Multi-AZ high availability? A: Deploy instances across multiple AZs, use ELB.
160.
Q: Scenario: Single AZ fails, app downtime. Fix? A: Deploy Multi-AZ ASG with cross-AZ load balancer.
161.
Q: What is ELB health check? A: Periodically pings instance endpoint; unhealthy instances removed from load balancer.
162.
Q: Scenario: ELB keeps removing instance. Check? A: Security group, response codes, app listening port.
163.
Q: Difference between AZ and region? A: Region = geographical area; AZ = isolated datacenter within region.
164.
Q: Scenario: Cross-region disaster recovery. How to deploy EC2? A: Replicate AMI, data, and ASG in secondary region; optionally use Route53 for failover.
165.
Q: How to handle sticky sessions? A: Enable ELB session stickiness or use client-side cookies.
166.
Q: Scenario: Need minimum 5 instances always running. How? A: Set ASG MinSize=5, DesiredCapacity=5.
167.
Q: Scenario: Reduce over-provisioning at night. How? A: Use scheduled scaling policies or target tracking with metrics.
168.
Q: What is target tracking scaling policy? A: Auto scale instances to maintain metric (e.g., CPUUtilization) near target.
169.
Q: Scenario: App CPU < 20% but ASG not scaling down. Check? A: Cooldown period may prevent immediate scale-in.
170.
Q: Difference between ASG scaling policies: simple, step, target tracking? A: Simple = one step, step = multiple step thresholds, target tracking = automatic based on metric.
171–200: Auto Scaling & High Availability
171.
Q: Scenario: Auto Scaling not triggering. Check? A: Verify CloudWatch metric, scaling policy, cooldown period, min/max instances.
172.
Q: ASG scale-in fails. Possible reasons? A: Lifecycle hooks delaying termination, instance in service with ELB, cooldown period.
173.
Q: Scenario: Scheduled scale-out for batch jobs. Approach? A: Configure scheduled scaling policy with exact time and instance count.
174.
Q: ASG instance unhealthy but not replaced. Why? A: Incorrect health check type (EC2 vs ELB), grace period too long.
175.
Q: Scenario: Maintain 3 instances minimum. How? A: ASG MinSize=3, DesiredCapacity=3.
176.
Q: How to implement Multi-AZ ASG? A: Launch instances across multiple AZs; ELB distributes traffic.
177.
Q: Scenario: ELB removes healthy instance. Why? A: Health check misconfiguration, app listening port, SG restrictions.
178.
Q: Difference between step and target tracking policy? A: Step = different actions for thresholds; target tracking = maintain metric at target.
179.
Q: Scenario: Scale down not reducing cost. Why? A: MinSize too high, ASG cooldown, metric thresholds not met.
180.
Q: Scheduled vs dynamic scaling? A: Scheduled = known time events; dynamic = real-time metric-based.
181.
Q: Scenario: CPU < 20% but instances not terminated. Solution? A: Check cooldown period, metric evaluation period, step scaling thresholds.
182.
Q: ASG cross-region support? A: No; ASG operates per region; use multiple ASGs for cross-region DR.
183.
Q: Scenario: Batch processing spikes CPU. How to handle? A: Use scheduled or target-tracking ASG to scale out during batch.
184.
Q: ASG minimum instances for SLA? A: Set MinSize to maintain required availability.
185.
Q: Scenario: AZ failure. How ASG maintains availability? A: Instances launched in other AZs automatically to meet desired capacity.
186.
Q: Health check types in ASG? A: EC2 (instance running), ELB (application responsiveness).
187.
Q: Scenario: ASG not replacing unhealthy instance. Check? A: Health check configuration, ELB attachment, termination policies.
188.
Q: Lifecycle hooks purpose? A: Pause scale-in/out to perform custom actions (drain connections, backup).
189.
Q: Scenario: Need zero-downtime deployment with ASG. How? A: Use Blue/Green deployment, replace instances gradually.
190.
Q: ASG integration with CloudWatch? A: Metrics trigger scaling policies (CPU, Network, custom metrics).
191.
Q: Scenario: ASG scaling too slow. How to improve? A: Reduce cooldown period, use step policies, adjust evaluation periods.
192.
Q: ASG scaling limits? A: MaxSize for upper limit; MinSize for lower limit.
193.
Q: Scenario: Multi-AZ EC2 HA with ASG & ELB. How? A: Deploy instances across AZs, ELB distributes traffic; ASG maintains capacity.
194.
Q: Target tracking policy example? A: Maintain average CPU at 50% → ASG scales up/down automatically.
195.
Q: Scenario: ASG scales incorrectly during low load. Check? A: Verify CloudWatch metric, evaluation period, step scaling thresholds.
196.
Q: Spot instances in ASG. Scenario? A: Configure Mixed Instances Policy → on-demand base, spot for bursts.
197.
Q: Scenario: ASG replacing healthy instance repeatedly. Fix? A: Health check misconfigured; check termination policies.
198.
Q: How to test ASG scaling policies? A: Simulate load via stress testing or CloudWatch metrics manipulation.
199.
Q: Scenario: Need consistent AZ distribution for instances. How? A: Set availability zones in ASG configuration.
200.
Q: Scenario: ASG not scaling due to metric delay. Fix? A: Enable detailed monitoring (1-min granularity).
201–250: Monitoring & CloudWatch
201.
Q: How to monitor EC2 performance? A: CloudWatch metrics: CPU, NetworkIn/Out, DiskRead/Write, StatusChecks, Memory (custom).
202.
Q: Scenario: Instance CPU high but CloudWatch normal. Why? A: Memory/IO bottleneck not visible in default metrics; enable detailed monitoring or custom metrics.
203.
Q: What are CloudWatch Alarms? A: Notifications triggered when metric crosses threshold.
204.
Q: Scenario: Receive repeated alarms for same instance. How to reduce? A: Adjust evaluation periods, enable OK state suppression, tune thresholds.
205.
Q: What is CloudWatch Logs? A: Centralized logging for EC2 (application/system logs).
206.
Q: Scenario: Application log monitoring for errors. Solution? A: Install CloudWatch Agent, push logs to CloudWatch Logs.
207.
Q: How to monitor ELB + EC2 metrics? A: CloudWatch metrics: RequestCount, Latency, HealthyHostCount.
208.
Q: Scenario: Latency spikes on EC2. How to investigate? A: Check CloudWatch CPU/Memory/Network, ELB metrics, application logs.
209.
Q: Difference between basic and detailed monitoring? A: Basic = 5-min intervals, Detailed = 1-min intervals (cost extra).
210.
Q: Scenario: You need 1-min granularity for auto-scaling. Solution? A: Enable detailed monitoring.
211–250: Monitoring & CloudWatch
211.
Q: Scenario: Need memory monitoring for EC2. How? A: Enable CloudWatch Agent and push custom memory metrics.
212.
Q: EC2 network performance metrics in CloudWatch? A: NetworkIn, NetworkOut, NetworkPacketsIn, NetworkPacketsOut.
213.
Q: Scenario: Instance shows high CPU but app slow. Check? A: Memory/IO metrics, CloudWatch Logs, Disk/Network throughput.
214.
Q: CloudWatch alarm triggers EC2 reboot. How? A: Alarm → SNS → Lambda → Systems Manager or API call to reboot instance.
215.
Q: Scenario: ELB latency high. Investigate? A: Check EC2 CPU/memory, network metrics, application logs, placement group.
216.
Q: Detailed vs basic monitoring? A: Basic = 5-min; Detailed = 1-min intervals.
217.
Q: Scenario: Auto Scaling requires 1-min metrics. Solution? A: Enable detailed monitoring on EC2.
218.
Q: How to aggregate CloudWatch logs across multiple EC2s? A: Use centralized CloudWatch Logs group with subscriptions.
219.
Q: Scenario: Alarm flapping frequently. Fix? A: Adjust threshold, evaluation periods, or use anomaly detection.
220.
Q: CloudWatch custom metrics example? A: App response time, queue length, memory utilization.
221.
Q: Scenario: EC2 app crashes silently. How to debug? A: CloudWatch Logs, X-Ray tracing, detailed monitoring.
222.
Q: Scenario: Disk IO bottleneck detected. Fix? A: Upgrade EBS volume, enable EBS-optimized instance, check instance type.
223.
Q: EC2 CPU credit exhaustion scenario. Solution? A: Burstable T2/T3 instance, monitor CPUCreditBalance, consider larger instance.
224.
Q: Scenario: CloudWatch alarm triggers at wrong time. Fix? A: Adjust evaluation period, threshold, or metric aggregation.
225.
Q: EC2 application latency monitoring. Tool? A: CloudWatch metrics, CloudWatch Logs, X-Ray traces.
226.
Q: Scenario: Need historical metric analysis. Solution? A: CloudWatch metrics history, export to S3, use Athena/QuickSight.
227.
Q: Scenario: EC2 auto-recovery trigger fails. How to investigate? A: Check CloudWatch Alarm, IAM permissions, Auto Recovery enabled.
228.
Q: Scenario: Multiple EC2 metrics need centralized alerting. Solution? A: CloudWatch dashboard + alarms + SNS notifications.
229.
Q: Scenario: Instance health checks failing intermittently. Fix? A: Analyze system logs, ELB health, network config, instance metrics.
230.
